{
  "text": "Robust behavioral rhythmicity in AhRKO mice, nevertheless, does not substantiate immediate rejection of the hypothesis that AhR has a role in circadian rhythm. Robust rhythmicity is observed in mice bearing single mutations of known clock genes [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In fact, deletion of a single clock gene rarely causes complete disruption of rhythmicity [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , with the exception of severe disruption observed in Bmal1 knockouts [CITATION_7] . Conversely, deletion of 2 clock genes often results in clear behavioral arrythmicity [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Robust rhythmicity in Clock null mice [CITATION_11] occurs because NPAS2 can functionally substitute for CLOCK [CITATION_12] . Similarly, a protein that shares redundancy with AhR may compensate for the complete absence of AhR. Therefore, it would be interesting to study the circadian phenotype of AhR mutant or AhRKO mice that have deletion of another clock gene such as Clock or Npas2.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "21409748",
